\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 (44:6\endash 13) }{\f0\fs24\b1 Family\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Home}{\f0\fs24 : Are we willing to stand by the family? This is the second test of loyalty: being willing to stand by the family no matter what confronts them.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 a. There was a strong charge made against the brothers (v. 6). The steward quickly caught the brothers and leveled the charge of stealing against them.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 b. But they made a clear declaration of innocence (v. 7).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab They strongly declared their honesty: since they had returned the money they had found in their sacks on their first trip, why would they steal silver or gold now (vv. 7}{\f0\fs24\super b}{\f0\fs24 \endash 8)?}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab Note that they declared their willingness to stand together as a family unit (v. 9). They were so confident of their innocence, they made a rash suggestion: if the silver cup was found stolen by any one of them, let him be executed, and the other brothers would become slaves of Joseph.}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2;ref=Bible.Ge44.6-13;off=0;ctx=avity$E2$80$9D_(1_Ti._3:4).$0A~2_(44:6$E2$80$9313)_Family$E2$80$94H"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 355). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 But note what they did: they proved their loyalty to the family. They passed the first stage of the test given by Joseph, passed it with flying colors. They were not going to forsake Benjamin. They were not going to allow even one member to be ripped apart from the family. The steward had said the innocent brothers were free: they could turn and go home. But this they were not going to do. They were going to stand together as a family. Together, they loaded their donkeys and returned to the city where the governor, Joseph, was waiting to charge them with the crime of stealing and most likely to enslave them (v. 13). When they walked into Joseph\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s house, he would learn what he had hoped: the brothers had undergone a tremendous change within their hearts. They were learning the great importance of }{\f0\fs24\i1 the chosen family}{\f0\fs24 : they were now willing to stand together as }{\f0\fs24\i1 the chosen family of believers}{\f0\fs24 . They were now willing to stand together to face whatever might come, no matter how terrible the situation was.}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2;ref=Bible.Ge44.6-13;off=2428;ctx=_nor_where_to_turn.$0A~But_note_what_they_d"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 355). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 (44:14\endash 17) }{\f0\fs24\b1 Family\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Forgiveness}{\f0\fs24 : Are we willing to seek forgiveness with the family? This is the third test of loyalty: being willing to seek forgiveness with the family no matter how serious the failing. Some twenty years earlier, the brothers had failed in the most terrible way possible for a person to fail: they had threatened to kill Joseph but ended up selling him into slavery. And they had never confessed their sin to anyone so far as is known: not to their father nor to God and, of course, never to Joseph. They needed to confess it to all three, especially to God. Now they were going to get the opportunity to confess to God and to Joseph. Would they pass this test? And if so, would they do it begrudgingly or with the same flying colors they had just demonstrated with Benjamin? Were the sons going to confess and repent in order to be converted, become true followers of God? Note what happened when they confronted Joseph.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 a. There was a strong united act: they all demonstrated humility together (vv. 14\endash 15). As soon as they entered the house of Joseph, they fell to the floor bowing before him. Joseph was no doubt overjoyed to see them all together standing by the side of their brother Benjamin. He now knew they were committed to stand together as a family, every one of them. Now, with God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s help, he needed to lead them to confession and repentance of their sin and to a commitment to stand together in following God}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2;ref=Bible.Ge44.14-17;off=2;ctx=ous$E2$80$9D_(1_Pe._3:8).$0A3_~(44:14$E2$80$9317)_Family$E2$80$94Fo"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 356). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 1)\tab Note their confession: God }{\f0\fs24\i1 had uncovered and found out their sin}{\f0\fs24 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 not just Benjamin\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s sin, but their sin, the sin for which they were all guilty. Judah was confessing that they were all guilty of sin, and God was now punishing them for it. God was punishing Benjamin, yes, but also punishing them for the sin they had committed in the past, the terrible sin of having sold their brother into slavery. Judah did not mention this sin publicly. That had already been done earlier in the presence of Joseph and his interpreter (Ge. 42:21\endash 24). But the meaning of Judah\u8217\'92s confession is clear: God had uncovered the sins of all the brothers, and they were now ready and willing to bear God\u8217\'92s punishment. They were now ready to become the slaves of Joseph, all of them together, for they were all guilty before God (v. 16).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab Note the declaration of belief in God: that He holds us accountable.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab Note the confession: they were all guilty of sin.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab Note the repentance: they were now ready and willing to follow God\u8217\'92s will even if it meant being punished for their sins.}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2;ref=Bible.Ge44.14-17;off=2373;ctx=r_all_the_brothers.$0A~1)_Note_their_confes"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 356). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 c. The test continued: Joseph just felt compelled to prove that the brothers were totally loyal to each other and to the family of God (v. 17). He declared that he could not enslave the innocent brothers, only the brother who had stolen the cup. Then he charged all the brothers to leave and go back home, all except Benjamin, the suspected thief.}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2;ref=Bible.Ge44.14-17;off=4424;ctx=osen_family_of_God.$0A~c._The_test_continue"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 356). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
