\pard\plain \intbl\itap1\qj{\f0\fs24\b1\scaps\cb5\highlight5 Deeper Study}{\f0\fs24\b1\cb5\highlight5  # 1}
\par\plain \intbl\itap1{\f0\fs24\cb5\highlight5 (44:15) }{\f0\fs24\b1\cb5\highlight5 Divination\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Fortune-Telling\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Sorcery}{\f0\fs24\cb5\highlight5 : divination is a heathen custom that has been practiced throughout the ages in all civilizations. The particular practice mentioned here used either oil by itself or else water with gold or silver in the bottom of a bowl or cup. The rays of light reflecting from the oil or water would form certain designs that were supposed to reveal the future.}
\par\pard\plain \intbl\itap1\fi360\qj{\f0\fs24\cb5\highlight5 Did Joseph actually practice this heathen custom, practice it of his own free will? Or was he, as the governor of Egypt, expected to practice the custom? Did he practice it in order to accommodate the people\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s expectation? Or was Joseph just associating himself with the sacred cup in order to drive more fear into his brothers? Identifying the cup as a cup of divination would place far more value upon it. This would make the penalty for stealing it far worse. The brothers would sense far more guilt for having stolen it and expect a far stiffer sentence.}
\par\plain \intbl\itap1{\f0\fs24\cb5\highlight5 It is very unlikely that Joseph practiced divination, for God issues strict warnings against the practice. Joseph most likely was just referring to the cup as a cup of divination in order to strike more fear in the brothers. The more important the cup the more fear, and the more they feared, the more likely they were to turn away from Benjamin to let him face the sentence all alone. This test was going to show exactly how strongly they were committed to each other and to the family. If they were totally committed to the family, they would stand by the side of Benjamin, bearing the penalty with him. If they had any lack of loyalty whatsoever\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 any weakness of attachment to the family\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 they would leave Benjamin to face the penalty alone.}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2;ref=Bible.Ge44.14-17;off=7927;ctx=_die$E2$80$9D_(Eze._18:21).$0A~Deeper_Study_$23_1$0A(44"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 357). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.}
\par\plain \intbl\itap1\f0\fs24
