\par\plain {\f0\fs24 18-23}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Practically every commentary on Genesis stresses the strength of Judah\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s plea. In the speech, Judah stood forth as a magnificent picture of Christ, of His great intercession and voluntary sacrifice for mankind. The tenderness and warmth of his words and the love expressed for his father are seldom seen among men. And just imagine: this came from the heart of a man who had been so mean and sinful, so immoral and evil, that he had broken the heart of his father years before. Judah is a dynamic example of the glorious mercy of God. If Judah and his brothers could be saved, then any person can be saved.}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 b. Judah reminded Joseph of }{\f0\fs24\i1 the demand}{\f0\fs24  he had made of them. Note the facts Judah stressed (vv. 18\endash 23).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He reminded Joseph of his inquiry about their family, asking if they had a brother or father (v. 19).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He reminded Joseph of their father: that their father was old and had two other sons. One son was dead and the other son was the child of their father\u8217\'92s old age. And their father loved him dearly (v. 20).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He reminded Joseph of }{\f0\fs24\i1 his demand}{\f0\fs24  to bring Benjamin to Egypt to prove that they were telling the truth (v. 21).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He reminded Joseph of their caution and reservation: taking Benjamin from their father might kill him (v. 22).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He reminded Joseph of }{\f0\fs24\i1 his insistence}{\f0\fs24 : they had to bring Benjamin, or they would never be allowed to see the governor\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s face again; they would never be allowed to get any more food (v. 23).}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2;ref=Bible.Ge44.18-34;off=2269;ctx=werful_as_Judah$E2$80$99s.5$0A~Practically_every_co"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 358). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 c. Judah related how the brothers had told their father about }{\f0\fs24\i1 the demand}{\f0\fs24  of the governor (vv. 24\endash 29). Note that Joseph had no way to know about these facts. He was hearing for the very first time what had happened when his brothers had returned home to their father.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He related how the need for more food arose (v. 25).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He related how the sons reminded their father of }{\f0\fs24\i1 the demand}{\f0\fs24  of the governor: the youngest brother had to go with them (v. 26).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He related their father\u8217\'92s response: his wife had borne him two sons and one had been torn to pieces (vv. 27\endash 28).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab He related how their father feared losing the second son: losing him would kill their father (v. 29).}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 d. Judah related his great concern (vv. 30\endash 31). Note that his concern was not Benjamin\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s guilt or innocence nor the freedom or enslavement of the brothers. Judah\u8217\'92s concern was his father. He did not want the heart of his father to be broken. Judah loved his father so much that he did not even want him to suffer pain. Note what he related to the governor:}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab Their father\u8217\'92s life was closely bound up with Benjamin (v. 30).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab Their father would die if the boy were not with them when they returned home (v. 31}{\f0\fs24\super a}{\f0\fs24 ).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab The sons\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the servants of Joseph\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 would therefore be guilty of killing their father because they did not bring the boy home (v. 31}{\f0\fs24\super b}{\f0\fs24 ).}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 e. What now happened was very significant: Judah pleaded his case before Joseph, proving his loyalty and love to the family beyond any question.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 1)\tab Judah shared that he had personally become surety for Benjamin (v. 32). If he failed to take the boy to his father, then he would bear the blame for the rest of his life.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 2)\tab Judah then did an amazing thing. He offered to }{\f0\fs24\i1 sacrifice himself}{\f0\fs24  for Benjamin (vv. 32\endash 33). He asked Joseph to let him become the slave and to free Benjamin, letting him go home to his father (v. 32). He offered \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab to become the substitute for Benjamin}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab to accept the punishment due Benjamin}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab to bear the guilt for Benjamin}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab to suffer in behalf of Benjamin}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab to give his life for the life of Benjamin}
\par\pard\plain \tx1440\li1440\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 \bullet \tab to switch places with Benjamin}
\par\pard\plain \li1080\fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Note why Judah did this: because of his father. How could he possibly go back to his father if Benjamin were not with him? His father would suffer undue misery, and he, Judah, would have to see his father suffer the misery for the rest of his life (v. 23).}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2;ref=Bible.Ge44.18-34;off=3707;ctx=_more_food_(v._23).$0A~c._Judah_related_how"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, pp. 358\endash 359). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 Thought 2}{\f0\fs24 . Note how Judah became a magnificent picture of Christ in the above scene. Henry Morris states it well:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\i1 In this willingness to give his own life in place of his brother\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s, for the sake of his father, Judah becomes a beautiful type of Christ, more fully and realistically than even Joseph himself, who is often taken by Bible expositors as a type of Christ. \u8220\'93Hereby perceive we the love of God, because he laid down his life for us: and we ought to lay down our lives for the brethren\u8221\'94 (1 John 3:16)}{\f0\fs24 .}
\par\pard\plain \li1080\fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\i1 In fact, although Scripture does not say this in so many words, the problem as to why Judah, rather than Joseph, was selected to be the ancestor of the Messiah probably has its solution right here. Judah, in his willingness to sacrifice himself, the innocent for the guilty, had become the most Christlike of all his brothers}{\f0\fs24 .}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 This was it, the end of Judah\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s speech. Joseph now knew that God had done a marvelous work in their lives.}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2;ref=Bible.Ge44.18-34;off=6254;ctx=position_and_honor$3F$0A~Thought_2._Note_how_"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 359). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24}